&gt; they were too stunned to make a sound. The 
&gt; wolf cub simply sat down and looked at all 
&gt; of them, finally opening her mouth in a wide 
&gt; yawn. The image blurred and suddenly the 
&gt; little girl was back. She smiled innocently 
&gt; and said once again, &quot;Wolf&quot;, 
&gt; before toddling back over to fall asleep 
&gt; near her guardian mother. The gypsy man who 
&gt; had been about to speak stood there with his 
&gt; mouth hanging open. He had seen the trick 
&gt; before. Druids tended to travel and hunt 
&gt; that way as it was much more efficient then 
&gt; normal forms. But never had he seen anyone 
&gt; so young even attempt to transform. It was a 
&gt; mid-level spell. The girl should not have 
&gt; had enough power to do it even if she knew 
&gt; the words to the spell. As the child rolled 
&gt; over in her sleep, her left arm was 
&gt; stretched out with her palm face up. As 
&gt; Trilan’s eyes took in the picture, his eye 
&gt; was suddenly riveted on the girl’s wrist. It 
&gt; bore the mark. The mark the woman of several 
&gt; years ago had spoke of. He had dismissed her 
&gt; words as delusions inspired by her illness, 
&gt; yet here was the child with the mark of the 
&gt; moon on her arm… showing promises of great 
&gt; power at such an early age. 

&gt; The space around the campfire suddenly 
&gt; erupted with talk. It was amazing said one. 
&gt; It was unnatural said another. The girl’s 
&gt; guardian mother simply sat there with a 
&gt; stunned look on her face. She was a simple 
&gt; woman and was unprepared to deal with things 
&gt; of this nature. Within minutes the girl’s 
&gt; feat had spread throughout the Glade and a 
&gt; small gathering of the leaders of the Glade 
&gt; had taken place. Whispering to themselves, 
&gt; they decided it was best not to leave the 
&gt; girl with her foster parents any longer. 
&gt; They were unable to teach the girl the 
&gt; willpower she would need to control the 
&gt; powers she obviously had inside of her. That 
&gt; coupled with the fact that the girl was 
&gt; simply too young to be doing such things, 
&gt; they decided it was best if she left the 
&gt; glade for a few years before coming back to 
&gt; undertake serious training. Knowing nothing 
&gt; about the mark on her arm, nor what it 
&gt; ‘supposedly’ meant, they were unsure of who 
&gt; to send her with. Trilan quickly volunteered 
&gt; to take the girl with them, and the leaders, 
&gt; relieved at having something to do with her 
&gt; agreed readily. 

&gt; She was bundled up and given to Trilan who 
&gt; made a bed for her in his wagon. The gypsy’s 
&gt; decided it was best to leave then, rather 
&gt; then risk a scene by taking the girl away in 
&gt; the morning. 

&gt; Kitaira adjusted quickly to their nomadic 
&gt; lifestyle and grew to love Trilan like a 
&gt; father. Disagreeing with their decision not 
&gt; to train the girl right away, he had 
&gt; immediately taken the girl to Rivervale and 
&gt; began her studies with the leader of the 
&gt; Druid Guild there. He would leave her there 
&gt; for a week or two at a time, before picking 
&gt; her up again to travel with the band. He 
&gt; grew quite fond of her and enjoyed watching 
&gt; her practice her skills. Traveling with the 
&gt; gypsies forced Kitaira to become a little 
&gt; more social, though she still held part of 
&gt; herself in reserve. In her 9th year, she was 
&gt; returned to the Glade and stayed for an 
&gt; entire year learning as much as she could 
&gt; before the wanderlust that would infect her 
&gt; soul forever kicked in. She sought out 
&gt; Trilan’s band and traveled with him again, 
&gt; stopping and training whenever they neared 
&gt; Rivervale or the Glade. In between visits to 
&gt; the guild he taught her weaponry skills to 
&gt; protect herself. She soon became an expert 
&gt; at using one and two handed blunt weapons. 

&gt; It was in her 14th year that she began to 
&gt; feel a yearning to be on her own. She was 
&gt; mature beyond her years and she talked 
&gt; quietly with Trilan and it was agreed she 
&gt; would be allowed to go. He had fears about 
&gt; this, knowing things about her that she 
&gt; could not possibly know herself. Things her 
&gt; mother had told him for instance. He had 
&gt; shared with Kitaira as much as he remembered 
&gt; about her mother and how she had searched 
&gt; for her father but never found him. He knew 
&gt; this bothered the girl terribly, but he had 
&gt; never found the trail of Santho either. 
&gt; Trilan had spoke nothing of Alara’s 
&gt; predictions about her daughter however. He 
&gt; did not explain the significance of the mark 
&gt; on her arm. He thought he would wait a few 
&gt; more years before she was ready for that. He 
&gt; also feared she was unaware of the power she 
&gt; had. She was in her 14th year, yet had 
&gt; already mastered spells that had some much 
&gt; higher level Druids stumped. She shrugged 
&gt; this feat off by saying she was just lucky 
&gt; and that they just didn’t try hard enough. 
&gt; His biggest fear was the girl’s trusting 
&gt; nature however. She had matured into a 
&gt; beautiful creature. Having been surrounded 
&gt; by the gypsies most of her life, she had no 
&gt; reason to fear anyone, and was trustful of 
&gt; anyone, strangers or not. He was worried 
&gt; that this trustful naiveté along with her 
&gt; beauty would get her hurt. But he had 
&gt; prepared her as best he knew how, and he 
&gt; tried not to let her see how affected he was 
&gt; by her leaving. Looking back only once, she 
&gt; waved, as she tried to ignore the burning in 
&gt; her stomach. She was unused to feeling pain 
&gt; and was not entirely sure how to deal with 
&gt; it. 

&gt; Kitaira began her travels of the world 
&gt; alone. She would occasionally travel in 
&gt; groups when she felt it was safer to do so. 
&gt; She learned that there were not-so-nice 
&gt; people in the world and was forced to learn 
&gt; to battle in fierce conditions. She 
&gt; continued her studies though not as 
&gt; diligently as before. She would run across 
&gt; Trilan’s band once in awhile and they would 
&gt; have a tearful reunion. 

&gt; On a cold winter in her 19th year, she came 
&gt; across the familiar sight of a gypsy camped 
&gt; and was overjoyed to see familiar faces. She 
&gt; ran through the camp with joy searching for 
&gt; him, not even noticing that people were 
&gt; looking at her with odd faces. Not finding 
&gt; his wagon, she stopped at the leader of the 
&gt; gypsies to find him. With a solemn face he 
&gt; sat her down and explained that Trilan had 
&gt; died in battle a few months before. It was 
&gt; bad enough that he was gone, but he had died 
&gt; trying to get her a gift. Last time she had 
&gt; seen him, she had told him of a great 
&gt; reptile that guarded a staff she wished to 
&gt; possess. He had gone to get her the staff 
&gt; and the mighty creature had slain him. 
&gt; Stunned by the news, she soon flew into a 
&gt; rage. Why had he been taken from her. It 
&gt; wasn’t fair. 

&gt; Determined to have revenge she immediately 
&gt; transformed into her customary wolf form and 
&gt; was at the oasis in a matter of days. She 
&gt; walked the land for hours before finally 
&gt; hearing a shout that the creature was near. 
&gt; In a blind fury she began casting spells 
&gt; that she had never tried before, determined 
&gt; to kill the creature that had slain Trilan. 
&gt; It should have been a quick battle. The 
&gt; creature should have killed her where she 
&gt; stood. She was not nearly of the strength to 
&gt; take it down alone. But in her rage she paid 
&gt; no heed to what should have happened. 
&gt; Ignoring the creatures attempts to bite her 
&gt; she continued her relentless assault on it, 
&gt; not realizing that she had drawn quite a 
&gt; crowd in the process. Tiring however, she 
&gt; let her concentration slip and he broke free 
&gt; of the root she had placed him in. With one 
&gt; quick movement she felt his teeth sink into 
&gt; her leg and she screamed in pain. His teeth 
&gt; still clamped down, she threw the last spell 
&gt; she knew at it and was relieved when the 
&gt; creature keeled over dead and she was able 
&gt; to pry it’s jaws off of her bleeding leg. A 
&gt; young cleric who had stood watching in awe 
&gt; used all his powers to heal the gaping 
&gt; wound. He did his best, but as he was young, 
&gt; the creature left a scar that she would 
&gt; carry always as a reminder. She took the 
&gt; staff he guarded and then proceeded to skin 
&gt; the creature and have a tunic made for 
&gt; herself. Only then did she allow herself to 
&gt; mourn Trilan’s loss. She did this alone. In 
&gt; the forest which was her home. 

&gt; She returned to her solitary ways and for 
&gt; the next two years traveled the country 
&gt; again, seeking something. She didn’t know 
&gt; what was driving her, nor where she was 
&gt; going, but she continued on. She met new 
&gt; people and ran across old acquaintances. She 
&gt; learned to love elven wine and hate the 
&gt; roots she foraged. She learned to swim 
&gt; despite her unnatural fear of deep water. 
&gt; She was greeted with a smile in most places 
&gt; where she was known. Her beauty kept some 
&gt; people at bay; others gave it a shot and 
&gt; were gently turned away. 

&gt; Somewhere along the way she freed a young 
&gt; black wolf cub from a trap he was caught in. 
&gt; Increasingly bold he began to follow her, 
&gt; always staying a few yards back. Amused by 
&gt; his actions she began to talk to him as she 
&gt; traveled. After tiring of calling him simply 
&gt; Wolf, she began to call him Tanthos. 
&gt; Gradually he began to sneak up close to her 
&gt; fires at night and eventually let her pet 
&gt; and feed him. They had been inseparable ever 
&gt; since; his keen ears and sharp teeth saving 
&gt; her on more than one occasion. He knew her 
&gt; moods better than any other; knowing when to 
&gt; stay away or when to come close. 

&gt; As she traveled she grew stronger and 
&gt; learned many skills to keep her alive while 
&gt; alone. She remembered Trilan’s tale of her 
&gt; mother searching for her father and did her 
&gt; best to keep her ears open for any word of a 
&gt; man called Santho, but so far she had heard 
&gt; nothing. She gradually lost interest in 
&gt; finding him, as she considered Trilan more 
&gt; of a father then anyone else. She never did 
&gt; overcome Trilan’s greatest fear though; she 
&gt; remained innocent and far too trustful of 
&gt; most that she met. It was through this 
&gt; naiveté that she ended up on a journey to 
&gt; Freeport with what, for her, could be 
&gt; considered a close friend, and a wizard whom 
&gt; she barely knew. What should have been a 
&gt; simple trip turned into a nightmare of 
&gt; deceit and death. She ended up wounded badly 
&gt; and fleeing for her life; carrying a deadly 
&gt; packet of herbs with her. Stumbling into a 
&gt; tavern in Freeport, she was befriended by an 
&gt; odd assortment of people there. Her goal had 
&gt; been merely to return the packet to it’s 
&gt; rightful owner, but so far she had been 
&gt; unable to do this. The wizard had tracked 
&gt; her down and was probably even now looking 
&gt; for her and the herbs he needed so badly. In 
&gt; the midst of worrying about him, she was 
&gt; taken hostage by a different ruthless wizard 
&gt; who had plans of his own. To escape, she had 
&gt; been forced to create something so horrid 
&gt; she could not even speak it’s name. And so 
&gt; she ran… back into the forest that was her 
&gt; home; where she was most at home… so that 
&gt; she could cleanse herself of the guilt she 
&gt; carried; just as she had when she lost 
&gt; Trilan. 
